{"id":"1603.06863","submitter":"M\\'at\\'e Lehel Juh\\'asz","authors":"M\\'at\\'e Lehel Juh\\'asz","title":"A universal linear algebraic model for conformal geometries","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.MG","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  This article describes an entirely algebraic construction for developing\nconformal geometries, which provide models for, among others, the Euclidean,\nspherical and hyperbolic geometries. On one hand, their relationship is usually\nshown analytically, through a framework comparing the measurement of distances\nand angles in Cayley-Klein geometries, including Lorentzian geometries, as done\nby F. Bachmann and later R. Struve. On the other hand, such a relationship may\nalso be expressed in a purely linear algebraic manner, as explained by D.\nHestens, H. Li and A. Rockwood.\n  The model described in this article unifies these approaches via a\ngeneralization of Lie sphere geometry. Like the work of N. Wildberger, it is a\npurely algebraic construction, and as such it works over any field of odd\ncharacteristic. It is shown that measurement of distances and angles is an\ninherent property of the model that is easy to identify, and the possible\nmodels are classified over the real, complex and finite fields, and partially\nin characteristic $2$, revealing a striking analogy between the real and finite\ngeometries.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 22 Mar 2016 16:46:38 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 8 Sep 2016 19:41:42 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 12 Jul 2018 16:31:43 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-07-13"}
