{"id":"1603.07227","submitter":"Mario Goldenbaum","authors":"Mario Goldenbaum, Holger Boche, H. Vincent Poor","title":"On Secure Computation Over the Binary Modulo-2 Adder Multiple-Access\n  Wiretap Channel","comments":"slightly longer version of a paper to be presented at IEEE ITW 2016","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1109/ITW.2016.7606788","report-no":null,"categories":"cs.IT math.IT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In this paper, the problem of securely computing a function over the binary\nmodulo-2 adder multiple-access wiretap channel is considered. The problem\ninvolves a legitimate receiver that wishes to reliably and efficiently compute\na function of distributed binary sources while an eavesdropper has to be kept\nignorant of them. In order to characterize the corresponding fundamental limit,\nthe notion of secrecy computation-capacity is introduced. Although determining\nthe secrecy computation-capacity is challenging for arbitrary functions, it\nsurprisingly turns out that if the function perfectly matches the algebraic\nstructure of the channel and the joint source distribution fulfills certain\nconditions, the secrecy computation-capacity equals the computation capacity,\nwhich is the supremum of all achievable computation rates without secrecy\nconstraints. Unlike the case of securely transmitting messages, no additional\nrandomness is needed at the encoders nor does the legitimate receiver need any\nadvantage over the eavesdropper. The results therefore show that the problem of\nsecurely computing a function over a multiple-access wiretap channel may\nsignificantly differ from the one of securely communicating messages.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 23 Mar 2016 15:13:02 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 30 Jul 2016 15:43:26 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-11-15"}
