{"id":"1603.07986","submitter":"Radu Ionicioiu","authors":"Radu Ionicioiu","title":"Schr\\\"odinger's Cat: Where Does The Entanglement Come From?","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Quanta 2017; 6: 57-60","doi":"10.12743/quanta.v6i1.64","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.gen-ph quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Schr\\\"odinger's cat is one of the most striking paradoxes of quantum\nmechanics that reveals the counterintuitive aspects of the microscopic world.\nHere, I discuss the paradox in the framework of quantum information. Using a\nquantum networks formalism, I analyse the information flow between the atom and\nthe cat. This reveals that the atom and the cat are connected only through a\nclassical information channel: the detector clicks $\\rightarrow$ the poison is\nreleased $\\rightarrow$ the cat is killed. No amount of local operations and\nclassical communication can entangle the atom and the cat, which are initially\nin a separable state. This casts a new light on the paradox.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 22 Mar 2016 20:47:42 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 13 Dec 2016 23:34:21 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Fri, 6 Oct 2017 21:57:37 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-10-10"}
